quizzes.textContent:
[h1]Variables[/h1]

Define all variables with a [b]name [/b]and a[b] data type[/b] before using them in a program. In cases in which you have multiple variables of the same type, it's possible to define them in one declaration, separating them with [b]commas[/b].[code format="cpp"][b]int [/b]a, b;
// defines two variables of type int[/code]
A variable can be assigned a value, and can be used to perform operations.
For example, we can create an additional variable called [b]sum[/b], and add two variables together.[code format="cpp"]int a = 30; 
int b = 15; 
[b]int sum = a + b;[/b]
// Now [b]sum [/b]equals 45[/code]
[note]Use the + operator to add two numbers.[/note]

[h1]Variables[/h1]

Let's create a program to calculate and print the sum of two integers.[code format="cpp" codeId="180"]#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

int main()
{
   int a = 30;
   int b = 12;
   int sum = a + b;

  [b] cout << sum;
[/b]
    return 0;
}

//Outputs 42[/code]
[note]Always keep in mind that all variables must be defined with a [b]name [/b]and a [b]data type[/b] before they can be used.[/note]
